There are several methods one may use to deal with the missing variables in the income column. Some may opt to drop the missing rows altogether, since the dataset is relatively large relative to the missing rows. However, I believe this is last resort, and as a result I will be looking into the distribution of income, to possibly predict said missing values.

I will be using the shapiro wilk test for normality, where the null hypothesis is that the data is not normally distributed, and the alternative hypothesis is that the data is normally distributed. This test also works well with small and medium sized datasets.

In [18]:
from scipy.stats import shapiro
Income_for_test = df["Income"].dropna()
statistic, p_value = shapiro(Income_for_test)
if p_value > 0.05:
    print(f"Income appears to be normally distributed (p-value = {p_value:.4f})")
else:
    print(f"Income appears to not be normally distributed (p-value = {p_value:.4f})")

Income appears to not be normally distributed (p-value = 0.0000)

The result from the shapiro test implies that income is not normally distributed, for robustness, I will also use the jarque-bera test, which is commonly used for small to medium sized datasets in economterics.

In [19]:
from scipy.stats import jarque_bera

stat, p_value = jarque_bera(Income_for_test)

alpha = 0.05  # Typical significance level
if p_value > alpha:
    print(f"Income appears to be normally distributed (p-value={p_value:.4f}")
else:
    print(f"Income appears to not be normally distributed (p-value={p_value:.4f})")

Income appears to not be normally distributed (p-value=0.0000)

This provides strong evidence that the data is not normally distributed, as a result, imputation of the mean would not suffice as an accurate representation of the missing values. However, due to the size of the dataset, using the median of the entire dataset may not be the ideal imputation.It is well documented within economic literature that income is correlated with education. As such, I will be looking at the Income distribution within each education subsection.

# Calculate z-scores for age
df['z_score_age'] = (df['Customer_Age'] - df['Customer_Age'].mean()) / df['Customer_Age'].std()

threshold = 3

# Extract outliers based on z-scores for age
age_outliers = df[df['z_score_age'].abs() > threshold]

The average age of the customers is 55, which is relatively close to retirement age in many countries. The age of enrollment is on average 44.22, so we can deduce that the average customer has been enrolled for 10 years. Additionally, on average customers made a purchase 49 days ago. The average income is higher than the median income, even prior to imputation. This is a bit contrary to empirical evidence, as this implies a right skew, whereas income is typically left skewed.

K-Means clustering is widely favored for its simplicity, ease of implementation, and computational efficiency, making it suitable for large datasets. It converges quickly and performs well with well-separated, spherical clusters, providing clear and interpretable results. Despite this, K-Means clustering is not without its disadvantages, as it is particularly sensitive to outliers, as a result, I will be scaling the features prior to implementation.

In [60]:
# Standardize the features
from sklearn.preprocessing import StandardScaler
scaler = StandardScaler()
df_scaled = scaler.fit_transform(df_to_scale)

Next, we must determine the ideal number of clusters, by using the elbow method.

In [61]:
from sklearn.cluster import KMeans
# Elbow method to find the optimal number of clusters
inertia = []
K = range(1, 11)

for k in K:
    kmeans = KMeans(n_clusters=k, random_state=42)
    kmeans.fit(df_scaled)
    inertia.append(kmeans.inertia_)

# Plotting the curve
plt.figure(figsize=(10, 6))
plt.plot(K, inertia, 'bx-')
plt.xlabel('Number of clusters')
plt.ylabel('Inertia')
plt.title('Elbow Method For Optimal k')
plt.show()

The diagram doesnt showcase a clear elbow point, as a result I am going to use silhouette and CHI analysis, to better pinpoint the optimal number of clusters.

In [62]:
from sklearn.metrics import silhouette_score

k_range = range(2, 11)  


silhouette_scores = []


for k in k_range:
  kmeans = KMeans(n_clusters=k)
  kmeans.fit(df_scaled)
  silhouette_score_val = silhouette_score(df_scaled, kmeans.labels_)
  silhouette_scores.append(silhouette_score_val)

# Finding the optimum
best_k = k_range[silhouette_scores.index(max(silhouette_scores))]

# Printing the silhouette
for k, score in zip(k_range, silhouette_scores):
  print(f"Number of clusters (k): {k}, Silhouette Score: {score:.4f}")

# Print the chosen k with the highest silhouette score
print(f"\nOptimal Number of Clusters (based on Silhouette Analysis): {best_k}")

from sklearn.metrics import calinski_harabasz_score

data = df_scaled
k_range = range(2, 11)

# Creating a dictionary to store
chi_scores = {}

#To loop through the different k values
for k in k_range:
  kmeans = KMeans(n_clusters=k)
  kmeans.fit(data)
  
  # Calculate CHI score
  chi_score_val = calinski_harabasz_score(data, kmeans.labels_)
  
  # Store scores in dictionaries
  chi_scores[k] = chi_score_val

# Find k with CHI score
best_k_chi = max(chi_scores, key=chi_scores.get)

print("\nCalinski-Harabasz Scores:")
for k, score in chi_scores.items():
  print(f"  Number of clusters (k): {k}, Score: {score:.4f}")

#To print the optimal K
print("\nPossible Optimal k values based on:")
print(f"  Calinski-Harabasz Index: {best_k_chi}")

# Calculate the composition of each cluster in terms of schooling
#This line of code, groups the dataset in unique cluster-education values, after which size creates an additional column
#In which the size of each unique pair is noted
#After which unstack creates a new dataframe, tranforming the different education levels into their respective columns
cluster_composition = df.groupby(['cluster', 'Education']).size().unstack()


# In this case, we have two values for composition that is 0 and 1. Within the loop we loc onto the row with index (cluster) 0
# In addition to the row with index(cluster) 1 and extract those values into composition
for cluster in cluster_composition.index:
    composition = cluster_composition.loc[cluster]

#Created a figure and axes with width of 8 inches and height of 6 inches
    fig,ax=plt.subplots(figsize=(8, 6))

# Plot pie chart, where composition captures the values within each row of the new dataframe, the index of this
# New dataframe is cluster,
    ax.pie(composition, labels=composition.index, autopct='%1.1f%%', startangle=140)

    # Set title
    ax.set_title(f'Cluster {cluster} - Composition by Schooling',fontweight='bold')

    # Show plot
    plt.tight_layout()
    plt.show()
